    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-04-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-04-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="146"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d146">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4–948</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 169</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-04-09">April 9,
                            1948</date>.<lb/>[Received April 20.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to enclose a copy of an
                        address<note n="88" xml:id="d146fn88">For text, see <hi rend="italic">United
                            States Relations With China</hi>, p. 847.</note> reputedly given by the
                    Generalissimo on April 4, 1948 at a meeting of the Central Executive Committee
                    of the Kuomintang. It was furnished the Embassy by an American correspondent,
                    who received it from a C. E. C. member. So far as we are aware, only a few
                    extracts from the address have appeared in the Chinese and foreign press, its
                    greater part having been suppressed.</p>
                <p>The main significance of the address lies in the fact that it formally and
                    specifically advises the Kuomintang to nominate a non-partisan to be candidate
                    to the presidency. The circumstances whereby the Generalissimo retreated from
                    this stand and agreed to become a presidential candidate are recorded in Embtel
                    630 dated April 8.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Ambassador: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lewis Clark</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister-Counselor of Embassy</hi>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
